observations.recommendation:
We recommended and
Management agreed to:
Direct the Supply/Property
Officer to:
a. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
b. Coordinate with all offices to prepare an updated list of all PPE items in their respective offices using “Annex A” of the aforementioned Circular;
c. Secure and verify the lists with the Property Cards (PCs) and the latest RPCPPE;
d. If no PCs were maintained and the latest RPCPPE was not prepared, submit the lists to the IC as a working paper for the conduct of the physical inventory and basis for the preparation of the Property Inventory Plan (PIP);
e. Based on the results of the physical inventory as reported in the RPCPPE by the IC, prepare/update all Property Cards and reconcile with accounting records to arrive at the correct balances of PPE accounts;
f. Prepare the Inventory and Inspection Reports of Unserviceable Properties for all obsolete and unserviceable properties;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
g. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
h. Update/prepare PPELCs for all PPE items per Accounting records;
i. Ensure that updated PPELCs reconcile with the controlling PPE General Ledger accounts;
j. Based on RPCPPE, take up the necessary accounting entries to recognize PPEs found at the station, PPEs lost, and the corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers/personnel; and
k. Collaborate with the Property Unit and determine the person/s accountable for the non-existing/ missing PPEs not otherwise disposed of or transferred.
Direct the Inventory Committee to:
l. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
m. Ensure that the inventory-taking activities are executed following the approved PIP;
n. Utilize the inventory working papers provided by the Property Unit and document the physical count in the ICF, taking into consideration the capitalization threshold of 50,000.00;
o. Tag with new property stickers all PPE items conducted and indicate the condition of the PPEs, such as in good condition, unserviceable, obsolete, etc;
p. Include in the physical count PPEs found at station but not included in the inventory working but with reasonable basis as owned by the LGU;
q. Describe as missing in the ICF the PPEs not found at station but listed in the inventory working paper;
r. Prepare the RPCPPE, upon completion of the physical count, and indicate all the necessary information required in the form, e.g., cost/value of the PPE, Property Stickers, etc.;
Direct the Property Unit, Accounting Unit, and the Inventory Committee to, henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

3.7 We recommended and Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant
and the Municipal Treasurer to:
3.7.1 Immediately transfer to the 20 percent DF bank current account the
amount of ₱2.950, the difference in the fund transfer shortage;
3.7.2 Transfer to the GF the amount of ₱7.731 million representing the GF
disbursement for DF PPAs;
3.7.3 Immediately stop the practice of disbursing 20 percent PPAs from the
GF;
3.7.4 Regularly transfer to the 20 percent DF bank current account the 20
percent NTA share;
3.7.5 Henceforth, monitor and make disbursements only when the fund’s bank
balance is sufficient.

10.5 We recommended and Management agreed to require the Property Officer,
Municipal Accountant, and Inventory Committee to:
10.5.1 Revisit pertinent provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 dated
January 30, 2020;
10.6 Inventory Committee to:
10.6.1 Undertake the annual physical inventory of all PPEs, prepare the
RPCPPE, and submit to the Accounting and Property Unit for
reconciliation and to the COA Team for validation;
10.6.2 Use the inventory working papers provided by the Property Officer as
reference in the conduct of the physical count and classify PPE items
under the appropriate RPCPPE;
10.6.3 Establish the value of 12 PPE items per Annex A.4 as per item 6.2.12 of
the same COA Circular;
10.7 Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to:
10.7.1 Reconcile the RPCPPE and the PPELC of accounting records to
ascertain the accuracy of the recorded PPE and to resolve the variance in
the total amount of ₱4.309 million;
10.7.2 Report in the IIRUP the two unserviceable items and request for
inspection, if necessary;

Require the designated GSO and Municipal Accountant to:

Reconcile the RIPE and the PPELC of accounting records to ascertain the correctness of PPE or vice versa to resolve the variance in the total amount of ₱2.925 million; 

Conduct physical count on 24 PPE items totaling ₱559.132 million;

Remove the 175 Semi-expendable items from the RPCPPE costing below 50,000.00 in the total amount of ₱2.136 million and integrate them in the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Properties Report; 

Reclassify Semi-expendable property which were recognized as PPE to the affected appropriate semi-expendable inventory accounts (if not yet issued to end-user), expense accounts (if issued within the year), or accumulated surplus/(deficit)/retained earnings accounts (if issued in prior years) pursuant to Item 3.1 of COA Circular 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;

Record all PPE items including those found at station in the Property Cards and Property Ledger Cards and to be maintained, henceforth, by the Property Unit and Accounting Unit, respectively;

Take appropriate action for the 1,605 PPE/Inventory items which are either without cost/value/donated/not taken up as PPE;

6.1 for PPE items without cost/value, coordinate with the source agency as to the status of said PPE items, if donated, 


6.1.1 secure Invoice and Receipt of Property and other related documents supporting the transfer of PPE; and

6.1.2   ascertain cost/value based on the market/fair value or by appraisal.

6.2 for Donated PPE items to other agency, furnish a copy of an Authority from the Municipal Mayor for the donation and Invoice and Receipt of Property donated;

6.3 for PPE items found at station, reported in the RPCPPE, and not taken as PPE per accounting record, coordinate with the source agency as to the status of said PPE items, if donated, 

      6.3.1 Secure Invoice and Receipt of Property and other related documents supporting the transfer of PPE; and

      6.3.2 Prepare Journal Entry Voucher to take up the donated PPE item.

Observe proper tagging of Property Numbers corresponding to the PPE sub-major account group and General Ledger account as provided in the different PPE categories in the Revised Chart of Accounts prescribed under the Accounting Manuals of the respective Sectors (Item 5.6 of COA Cir. 2020-006, 1/31/20);

Submit physical count on unserviceable PPEs and report the same in the IIRUP;

Utilize the RPCPPE format in conducting physical count of serviceable PPE for CY 2023 and years thereafter;

Maintain Property Ledger Cards for all purchased/acquired/donated PPEs for monitoring and to ease reconciliation with the GSO designate; and

Invite the COA Auditor/Representative to witness the succeeding physical inventory taking in CY 2023 and years thereafter.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to:
Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 22, 2022;
Collaborate and cause the immediate reconciliation of PPE records, reports, and balances;
Upon reconciliation of PPE, identify the items that are below the ₱50,000.00 capitalization threshold and cause the immediate reclassification thereof;
Take appropriate actions as provided for in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 22, 2022 such as, but not limited to: 1) Creation of Semi-Expendable Property Cards and Ledger Cards, 2) Preparation of Inventory Custodian Slips, and 3) Updating of Property Acknowledgement Receipts for those issued items.
Prepare a Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued (RegSPI)
Inform the Head of the Agency of the non-existing/missing PPEs without pending Request for Relief;
Henceforth comply with the provision of COA Circular No. 2022-004.
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Effect necessary adjustments in the financial records and reports reconciled items based on the reconciliation with the Supply Officer.
Reflect the restated balances in the next financial reporting period with corresponding disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

